article.description: Tan White scored a season-high 23 points to lead the Indiana Fever to a 90-62 victory over the Seattle Storm on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Fever's 51.5 percent shooting too much for Storm
article.linkText: White helps hot-shooting Fever run over Storm
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Once upon a time, Tamika Catchings had to do everything for the Indiana Fever to win games.

Sometimes she still does, but now she can trust her teammates to help carry the load. The Fever's bench scored 47 points in a 90-62 win over the Seattle Storm on Wednesday night.

Reserve Tan White scored a season-high 23 points and another bench player, Sheri Sam, added a season-best 15.

"Anybody can step up on any given night," Catchings said. "We had a balanced scoring attack. That's going to be a key thing for us as we look to win a championship -- not focusing on one person or two people."

Indiana coach Brian Winters couldn't remember seeing reserves score so many points in a WNBA game. Catchings said it was the best the Fever have played in her six-year career.

"We started off kind of slow, but once we picked it up it was like smooth sailing," she said. "Everything was hitting. Everything was connecting."

Catchings did her part with 14 points and 10 rebounds for her second double-double of the year. She became the 17th player in WNBA history to reach 3,000 career points when she made a 3-pointer with 3:48 left in the first quarter.

Tammy Sutton-Brown added 15 points and nine rebounds for Indiana (8-1), which won its fourth straight and snapped Seattle's two-game winning streak. The Fever have won their last three home games by a combined 72 points.

Janell Burse led Seattle (4-4) with 18 points, and Lauren Jackson added 17. Seattle shot 39 percent and made just two of 19 3-pointers.

Seattle made its first eight shots to take a 16-8 lead with 5:49 left in the first quarter. Seattle rookie Katie Gearlds hit a 3-pointer with 3.5 seconds left in the period to give the Storm a 26-21 lead. She finished with three points on 1-for-8 shooting.

Indiana started the second quarter on a 23-0 run while Seattle missed its first 10 shots of the period. Jackson finally scored with 2:28 left in the quarter, but the Fever led 50-30 at halftime. Indiana allowed a team record four points in the second quarter.

"At the end of the first, we started to play a little more zone, and we just continued it in the second," Winters said. "It was just a combination of they were missing and our slides in the zone were very good."

Jackson hoped her perimeter shooters just had an off night.

"If I were a coach, the next game, I would play zone against us by the way we played against their zone tonight," she said.

Jackson made a free throw after a technical foul on Winters to cut the Fever's lead to 56-41 in the third quarter, but Indiana responded with a 10-0 run.

Indiana shot 51.5 percent and outrebounded Seattle 41-24. It was the fourth time in franchise history the Fever have scored 90 or more points.

Seattle played in Chicago on Tuesday night, but Storm coach Anne Donovan said that wasn't an excuse.

"It was disappointing," she said. "We shot poorly and rebounded poorly. We need to control those areas."
